SIMPLE: gorgon
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gorgon
<hw>Gor"gon</hw> <pr>(g⟦ocir⟧r"g⟦ocr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>Gorgo</ets>, <ets>-onis</ets>, Gr. <grk>Gorgw`</grk>, fr.
<grk>gorgo`s</grk> terrible.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Gr. Myth.)</fld>
<def>One of three fabled sisters, Stheno, Euryale, and Medusa, with
snaky hair and of terrific aspect, the sight of whom turned the beholder
to stone. The name is particularly given to Medusa.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Anything very ugly or horrid.</def>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The brindled gnu. See
<er>Gnu</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gorgon</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Gorgon
<hw>Gor"gon</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Like a Gorgon; very ugly or
terrific; <as>as, a <ex>Gorgon</ex> face</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gorgonacea</ent>⟦br⟧
\'d8
